<article><h1>How to Stake Solana: A Complete Guide for Beginners</h1>
<p style="font-size:0.85rem;color:#8080a0;margin:8px 0 16px;">By <a href="/about.html" style="color:#FFD700;text-decoration:none;">Samuel Pason</a> · DogeKing Editor</p><p>Staking Solana lets you earn passive income on your SOL holdings while helping secure the network. Here is everything you need to know to start staking in 2026.</p><h2>What Is Staking?</h2><p>Staking means locking up your SOL tokens to help validate transactions on the Solana network. In return, you earn staking rewards - currently around 6-8% APY. Unlike mining, staking requires no specialized hardware. You just hold your tokens and delegate them to a validator who handles the technical work.</p><h2>Step-by-Step Staking Guide</h2><p>Step 1: Buy SOL on an exchange (Coinbase, Binance, Kraken). Step 2: Transfer to a non-custodial wallet (Phantom, Solflare, Backpack). Step 3: Choose a validator with good uptime and low commission (1-10%). Step 4: Delegate your SOL to the validator through your wallet's staking interface. Step 5: Start earning rewards immediately. Rewards are distributed automatically every epoch (approximately 2 days).</p><h2>Choosing a Validator</h2><p>Look for validators with at least 95% uptime, commission rates under 10%, and a reputable operator. Avoid validators with 0% commission - this is often a short-term promotional tactic. Diversify across 2-3 validators to reduce risk. Popular options include Laine, Coinbase Cloud, Figment, and Everstake.</p><h2>Risks</h2><p>Slashing (losing staked funds due to validator misbehavior) is extremely rare on Solana. The main risk is the lock-up period - some validators have a delay before you can unstake (usually 1-3 days). SOL price volatility also affects your total return. If SOL drops 20%, even 8% staking rewards won't offset the loss. Stake only what you can afford to hold long-term.</p></article>
